Read `.claude/FOCUS.md` first -- including its "build maximally
autonomously" policy. Build first, don't just analyze: pick the most
reasonable interpretation of an accumulated idea and build it, on its own
branch if it's not a continuation of the stated focus, flagged in
`.claude/QUESTIONS.md` and the report. Only actually stop and wait for
the user when the action itself can't be reverted -- an ordinary commit,
branch, or tracker POST never qualifies.

This command is designed to run unattended overnight, with no human
review step until the morning.

## 1. Orient

`git log --oneline -10`, current branch state, `README.md`, and
`.claude/FOCUS.md`. If the previous nightly run left work in progress
(check the last report under `~/reports/<PROJECT>/`), pick up from there
rather than starting over. Also fetch the full tracker backlog with
`&status=all&type=all` (see `../INTAKE.md`) so nothing already resolved
gets re-investigated, and so any new `type=feature` reports are visible
for the report's summary even though they won't be implemented.

**Any open report whose `note` starts with exactly `NIGHTLY:`** was
explicitly handed off by `/bug-sweep` as a real, fixable bug that was
just too big for a fast sweep (see that command's step 2) -- these are
ALWAYS in scope tonight, in addition to whatever FOCUS.md says, not
something FOCUS.md needs to mention by name. Note every one you find
before moving on, so step 3 doesn't miss one.

## 2. Re-verify anything a previous run touched, from scratch

Do not trust a prior run's own claims about what works -- run the
project's real test suite if it has one, or build a fresh local test
harness, and confirm independently before building further on top of it.

## 3. Push forward, building rather than just analyzing

Scope = FOCUS.md's stated focus, UNION every `NIGHTLY:`-flagged report
from step 1, UNION the accumulated `type=feature` backlog -- per
FOCUS.md's autonomy policy, build features too, not just summarize them.
Commit as you complete meaningful chunks; do not save it all for one
giant commit at the end.

A feature (or any distinct new idea, not a continuation of FOCUS.md's
stated focus) gets its own branch off `main`, named for what it is,
pushed on its own -- don't stack unrelated new work onto whatever branch
happens to be checked out. That's what "easy to roll back" means in
practice: undoing a bad call is not merging the branch, not untangling
one feature's commits from another's.

For each `NIGHTLY:`-flagged bug you fix, resolve it on the tracker the
same way `/bug-sweep` would, referencing the commit hash (see
`../INTAKE.md`) -- do not leave it for a future sweep to re-discover. For
each feature you build, note in `.claude/QUESTIONS.md` (step 5) which
branch it landed on -- that note IS the review point, not a request to
build it.

## 4. Stress-test what you built

Look for the scenarios a first pass typically misses -- edge cases, empty
states, deeper nesting/scale than the happy-path case, deep links into a
mid-state. Fix what breaks; note what's genuinely out of scope for
tonight.

## 5. Flag what you built, and anything needing the user's own judgment

Two things go here, both append-only (never overwrite or trim existing
entries), format `- **YYYY-MM-DD (nightly-batch):** <text>`:

- **Every feature/distinct new idea you built tonight** (step 3) -- which
  branch it landed on, what it does, in one or two lines. This IS the
  review point for something built without asking first -- it has to
  actually be findable.
- **A genuine judgment call needing the user's own decision** -- not
  "should I build this" (default: yes, per FOCUS.md), but something
  actually ambiguous: a real tradeoff, a "which of these two directions,"
  or a case you genuinely couldn't tell whether it crossed the
  irreversible-action line. Most nights have at most one of these; don't
  manufacture one.

## 6. Write the report

`~/reports/<PROJECT NAME -- fill in>/$(date +%Y-%m-%d).md`, and update
`~/reports/<PROJECT NAME>/LATEST.md` to match it. Cover exactly: what
shipped (with commit references), what broke and got fixed, what was
deliberately deferred and why (per FOCUS.md), any `NIGHTLY:`-flagged bugs
resolved, a summary of any new feature-backlog ideas seen since the last
report, and whether anything got appended to `.claude/QUESTIONS.md`
(point at it, don't duplicate its full text here). This is read once,
quickly, the next time this machine boots up -- write for that, not for
completeness's own sake.

## 7. Before finishing

Confirm every meaningful change has a real commit, pushed to origin.
An overnight run that is not saved anywhere didn't happen. If this
project's tracker backend supports it (see `../INTAKE.md`'s
`sweep-status` contract), POST a status update the same way `/bug-sweep`
does, so a live status readout reflects tonight's run too.
